<p class="eyebrow">Compatibility</p>
<h1>Know exactly which call features are supported before migration.</h1>
<p class="lede">The VoiceML compatibility page is explicit, searchable, and honest. Every verb, attribute, REST resource, and caveat is published as a clear support status rather than a broad promise.</p>
<p class="hero-actions">
	<a class="btn btn-primary" href="#checker">Paste XML</a>
	<a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/voiceml/migrate/">Migration guide</a>
</p>

<section class="section-block" data-section-type="matrix-summary">
	<h2>Matrix summary</h2>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Supported</strong> — Core call-control verbs and voice resources that engineering has verified.</li>
		<li><strong>Partial</strong> — Features that work with documented caveats, such as platform or media-module limitations.</li>
		<li><strong>Unsupported</strong> — Features intentionally outside scope, including payment handling and unrelated hosted products.</li>
		<li><strong>Native VoiceTel path</strong> — Products such as numbers and messaging link to VoiceTel-native product pages when they are not part of the compatible voice API surface.</li>
	</ul>
</section>

<section class="section-block" data-section-type="checker-copy">
	<h2>Client-side XML checker</h2>
	<p>The checker parses XML in the browser, matches verbs and attributes against the compatibility matrix, and returns compatible, compatible with caveats, or not supported. Pasted XML is not sent to a server.</p>
</section>
